{"key":"processedPost-19220710","value":{"id":19220710,"first":19217094,"last":19221233,"when":1386072885,"utime":"12/03/13 02:14 PM","content":"You can clone from just about any fleshy part of the mushroom.&nbsp; However, you're going to get less than ideal performance from grocery store mushrooms.&nbsp; First, they've already expanded the mycelium, and then fruited it.&nbsp; If you clone and start over, you're starting from old cell lines.&nbsp; You'll be miles ahead to obtain a low-time culture.<br /><br />When you <a href=\"http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Mushroom-Cloning\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer noopener\">clone</a>, tear the stem or cap in half and carefully cut a tiny piece of mycelium from the inside tissue which has never been exposed to air.<br />RR","title":"Re: Tissue-specific cloning","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}